</div><div class="info-panel__citations info-panel__item"><a href="#tab-citations" class="btn btn--inverse btn--slim" data-toggle="tooltip" data-original-title="View Citations" aria-label="View Citations"><i aria-hidden="true" class="icon-format_quote"></i></a></div><div class="info-panel__formats info-panel__item"><a href="#core-collateral-purchase-access" class="btn btn--access" data-toggle="tooltip" data-original-title="Go to purchase options" aria-label="Go to purchase options"><i aria-hidden="true" class="icon-lock-open"></i><span class="link-text">Get Access</span></a></div></div></div></div></header><div data-core-nav="header" data-extent="frontmatter"><div class="core-nav-wrapper core-container" aria-label="Article navigation"><div><button aria-controls="article_sections_menu" aria-expanded="false" aria-label="Toggle section navigation menu"><i class="icon-list" aria-hidden="true"></i><span>Contents</span></button><nav id="article_sections_menu" aria-label="Contents" data-core-nav="article"><ul><li><a href="#abstract">Abstract</a></li><li><a href="#core-sec-figures">Figures</a></li><li><a href="#bibliography">References</a></li></ul></nav></div><nav id="article_collateral_menu"><ul class="collateral-pill" data-core-nav="collateral"><li><a href="#core-collateral-info" aria-controls="core-collateral-info" aria-disabled="true" disabled="true" data-toggle="tooltip" data-placement="left" data-original-title="Information & Authors" title="Information & Authors" aria-expanded="false"><i aria-hidden="true" class="icon-info"></i><span class="sr-only">Information & Authors</span></a></li><li><a href="#core-collateral-metrics" aria-controls="core-collateral-metrics" aria-disabled="true" disabled="true" data-toggle="tooltip" data-placement="left" data-original-title="Metrics & Citations" title="Metrics & Citations" aria-expanded="false"><i aria-hidden="true" class="icon-metrics"></i><span class="sr-only">Metrics & Citations</span></a></li><li><a href="#core-collateral-purchase-access" aria-controls="core-collateral-purchase-access" aria-disabled="true" disabled="true" data-toggle="tooltip" data-placement="left" data-original-title="Get Access" title="Get Access" aria-expanded="false"><i aria-hidden="true" class="icon-lock-open"></i><span class="sr-only">Get Access</span></a></li><li><a href="#core-collateral-references" aria-controls="core-collateral-references" aria-disabled="true" disabled="true" data-toggle="tooltip" data-placement="left" data-original-title="References" title="References" aria-expanded="false"><i aria-hidden="true" class="icon-references"></i><span class="sr-only">References</span></a></li><li><a href="#core-collateral-figures" aria-controls="core-collateral-figures" aria-disabled="true" disabled="true" data-toggle="tooltip" data-placement="left" data-original-title="Figures" title="Figures" aria-expanded="false"><i aria-hidden="true" class="icon-photo"></i><span class="sr-only">Figures</span></a></li><li><a href="#core-collateral-tables" aria-controls="core-collateral-tables" aria-disabled="true" disabled="true" data-toggle="tooltip" data-placement="left" data-original-title="Tables" title="Tables" aria-expanded="false"><i aria-hidden="true" class="icon-table"></i><span class="sr-only">Tables</span></a></li><li><a href="#core-collateral-media" aria-controls="core-collateral-media" aria-disabled="true" disabled="true" data-toggle="tooltip" data-placement="left" data-original-title="Media" title="Media" aria-expanded="false"><i aria-hidden="true" class="icon-play-circle-filled"></i><span class="sr-only">Media</span></a></li><li><a href="#core-collateral-share" aria-controls="core-collateral-share" aria-disabled="true" disabled="true" data-toggle="tooltip" data-placement="left" data-original-title="Share" title="Share" aria-expanded="false"><i aria-hidden="true" class="icon-share"></i><span class="sr-only">Share</span></a></li></ul></nav></div></div><div data-core-wrapper="content"><div id="abstracts" data-extent="frontmatter"><div class="core-container"><section id="abstract" property="abstract" typeof="Text" role="doc-abstract"><h2 property="name">Abstract</h2><div role="paragraph">Breast lymphoma is a rare hematologic neoplasm that originates in the breast lymphoid tissue and includes primary breast lymphoma (PBL) and secondary breast lymphoma (SBL). PBL involves the breast lymphoid tissue in the absence of previously identified extramammary lymphoma and widespread disease. SBL is the most common metastasis to the breast, accounting for 17% of metastatic disease to the breast. PBL and SBL usually demonstrate imaging phenotypes that overlap with those of primary breast carcinoma, which makes a prospective diagnosis of breast lymphoma challenging. These nonspecific imaging features include an iso- to hyperdense oval mass or masses at mammography, a hypoechoic or mixed-echogenicity hypervascular mass at US, an enhancing mass with type II kinetics at MRI, and high fluorine 18–fluorodeoxyglucose avidity at PET. In cases of suspected lymphoma, reviewing the clinical history, using appropriate biopsy techniques, and evaluating for multiplicity, bilaterality, and distant disease are critical for diagnosis and management. A patient with PBL generally has an earlier clinical presentation with a palpable abnormality and a solitary imaging finding. In contrast, multiple masses in an older patient and an occult clinical presentation favor an SBL diagnosis.</div><div role="paragraph"><sup>©</sup>RSNA, 2019</div></section></div></div><section id="bodymatter" data-extent="bodymatter" property="articleBody" typeof="Text"><div class="core-container"><section aria-labelledby="denial-block-title" class="denial-block "><h2 id="denial-block-title" class="denial-block__title">Get full access to this article</h2><p class="denial-block__text">View all available purchase options and get full access to this article.</p><div class="denial-block__cta"><a href="#core-collateral-purchase-access" class="btn btn--access"><i aria-hidden="true" class="icon-lock-open"></i><span>Get Access</span></a></div><footer class="denial-block__footer"><span>Already a Subscriber? </span><span>Sign in as an </span><a href="/action/showLogin?redirectUri=/doi/10.1148/rg.2019180097">individual</a><span> or via your </span><a href="/action/ssostart?uri=/doi/10.1148/rg.2019180097">institution</a></footer></section></div></section><section id="backmatter" data-extent="backmatter"><div class="core-container"><section id="core-sec-figures" data-type="figures"><h2>Figures</h2><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig1a" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2019180097/asset/images/large/rg.2019180097.fig1a.jpeg" height="2093" width="1517" aria-labelledby="fig1a" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 1a</span>. New palpable lump in a 47-year-old woman. <b>(a)</b> Craniocaudal (CC) and mediolateral oblique (MLO) mammograms of the left breast show a solitary oval circumscribed mass (arrows) in the left lower central breast. <b>(b)</b> CC and MLO mammograms of the right breast show no findings of malignancy. <b>(c, d)</b> US images of the left breast show an oval indistinct mass (arrow) with mixed echogenicity. The results of a pathologic examination confirmed primary B-cell NHL.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2019180097&amp;id=fig1a">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig1b" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2019180097/asset/images/large/rg.2019180097.fig1b.jpeg" height="2093" width="1729" aria-labelledby="fig1b" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 1b</span>. New palpable lump in a 47-year-old woman. <b>(a)</b> Craniocaudal (CC) and mediolateral oblique (MLO) mammograms of the left breast show a solitary oval circumscribed mass (arrows) in the left lower central breast. <b>(b)</b> CC and MLO mammograms of the right breast show no findings of malignancy. <b>(c, d)</b> US images of the left breast show an oval indistinct mass (arrow) with mixed echogenicity. The results of a pathologic examination confirmed primary B-cell NHL.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2019180097&amp;id=fig1b">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig1c" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2019180097/asset/images/large/rg.2019180097.fig1c.jpeg" height="1198" width="1241" aria-labelledby="fig1c" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 1c</span>. New palpable lump in a 47-year-old woman. <b>(a)</b> Craniocaudal (CC) and mediolateral oblique (MLO) mammograms of the left breast show a solitary oval circumscribed mass (arrows) in the left lower central breast. <b>(b)</b> CC and MLO mammograms of the right breast show no findings of malignancy. <b>(c, d)</b> US images of the left breast show an oval indistinct mass (arrow) with mixed echogenicity. The results of a pathologic examination confirmed primary B-cell NHL.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2019180097&amp;id=fig1c">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig1d" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2019180097/asset/images/large/rg.2019180097.fig1d.jpeg" height="1198" width="1207" aria-labelledby="fig1d" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 1d</span>. New palpable lump in a 47-year-old woman. <b>(a)</b> Craniocaudal (CC) and mediolateral oblique (MLO) mammograms of the left breast show a solitary oval circumscribed mass (arrows) in the left lower central breast. <b>(b)</b> CC and MLO mammograms of the right breast show no findings of malignancy. <b>(c, d)</b> US images of the left breast show an oval indistinct mass (arrow) with mixed echogenicity. The results of a pathologic examination confirmed primary B-cell NHL.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2019180097&amp;id=fig1d">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig2a" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2019180097/asset/images/large/rg.2019180097.fig2a.jpeg" height="2783" width="1161" aria-labelledby="fig2a" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 2a</span>. Recurrent primary B-cell NHL in a 53-year-old woman with a history of stage I PBL in the right breast 15 years earlier who underwent screening mammography. <b>(a–c)</b> MLO mammogram obtained 1 year earlier <b>(a)</b> and the current screening MLO mammogram <b>(b)</b> and MLO magnified (<i>Mag</i>) view of the area of interest <b>(c)</b> show the development of an oval circumscribed mass (arrow in <b>b, c)</b>, which developed in the surgical bed. <b>(d)</b> US image shows an oval mass (arrow) with mixed echogenicity. <b>(e)</b> Axial PET image shows a mass with high fluorine 18 fluorodeoxyglucose (FDG) avidity (arrow). The results of a pathologic examination confirmed recurrent primary B-cell NHL.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2019180097&amp;id=fig2a">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig2b" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2019180097/asset/images/large/rg.2019180097.fig2b.jpeg" height="2783" width="1011" aria-labelledby="fig2b" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 2b</span>. Recurrent primary B-cell NHL in a 53-year-old woman with a history of stage I PBL in the right breast 15 years earlier who underwent screening mammography. <b>(a–c)</b> MLO mammogram obtained 1 year earlier <b>(a)</b> and the current screening MLO mammogram <b>(b)</b> and MLO magnified (<i>Mag</i>) view of the area of interest <b>(c)</b> show the development of an oval circumscribed mass (arrow in <b>b, c)</b>, which developed in the surgical bed. <b>(d)</b> US image shows an oval mass (arrow) with mixed echogenicity. <b>(e)</b> Axial PET image shows a mass with high fluorine 18 fluorodeoxyglucose (FDG) avidity (arrow). The results of a pathologic examination confirmed recurrent primary B-cell NHL.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2019180097&amp;id=fig2b">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig2c" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2019180097/asset/images/large/rg.2019180097.fig2c.jpeg" height="2783" width="930" aria-labelledby="fig2c" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 2c</span>. Recurrent primary B-cell NHL in a 53-year-old woman with a history of stage I PBL in the right breast 15 years earlier who underwent screening mammography. <b>(a–c)</b> MLO mammogram obtained 1 year earlier <b>(a)</b> and the current screening MLO mammogram <b>(b)</b> and MLO magnified (<i>Mag</i>) view of the area of interest <b>(c)</b> show the development of an oval circumscribed mass (arrow in <b>b, c)</b>, which developed in the surgical bed. <b>(d)</b> US image shows an oval mass (arrow) with mixed echogenicity. <b>(e)</b> Axial PET image shows a mass with high fluorine 18 fluorodeoxyglucose (FDG) avidity (arrow). The results of a pathologic examination confirmed recurrent primary B-cell NHL.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2019180097&amp;id=fig2c">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig2d" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2019180097/asset/images/large/rg.2019180097.fig2d.jpeg" height="768" width="1510" aria-labelledby="fig2d" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 2d</span>. Recurrent primary B-cell NHL in a 53-year-old woman with a history of stage I PBL in the right breast 15 years earlier who underwent screening mammography. <b>(a–c)</b> MLO mammogram obtained 1 year earlier <b>(a)</b> and the current screening MLO mammogram <b>(b)</b> and MLO magnified (<i>Mag</i>) view of the area of interest <b>(c)</b> show the development of an oval circumscribed mass (arrow in <b>b, c)</b>, which developed in the surgical bed. <b>(d)</b> US image shows an oval mass (arrow) with mixed echogenicity. <b>(e)</b> Axial PET image shows a mass with high fluorine 18 fluorodeoxyglucose (FDG) avidity (arrow). The results of a pathologic examination confirmed recurrent primary B-cell NHL.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2019180097&amp;id=fig2d">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig2e" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2019180097/asset/images/large/rg.2019180097.fig2e.jpeg" height="768" width="1129" aria-labelledby="fig2e" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 2e</span>. Recurrent primary B-cell NHL in a 53-year-old woman with a history of stage I PBL in the right breast 15 years earlier who underwent screening mammography. <b>(a–c)</b> MLO mammogram obtained 1 year earlier <b>(a)</b> and the current screening MLO mammogram <b>(b)</b> and MLO magnified (<i>Mag</i>) view of the area of interest <b>(c)</b> show the development of an oval circumscribed mass (arrow in <b>b, c)</b>, which developed in the surgical bed. <b>(d)</b> US image shows an oval mass (arrow) with mixed echogenicity. <b>(e)</b> Axial PET image shows a mass with high fluorine 18 fluorodeoxyglucose (FDG) avidity (arrow). The results of a pathologic examination confirmed recurrent primary B-cell NHL.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2019180097&amp;id=fig2e">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig3a" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2019180097/asset/images/large/rg.2019180097.fig3a.jpeg" height="1721" width="1764" aria-labelledby="fig3a" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 3a</span>. SBL in a 68-year-old woman with a history of splenomegaly who underwent screening mammography. <b>(a)</b> Bilateral MLO mammograms reveal diffuse bilateral skin (blue arrows) and trabecular (yellow arrows) thickening, with no mass. <i>Lt</i> = left, <i>Rt</i> = right. <b>(b, c)</b> Gray-scale <b>(b)</b> and color Doppler flow <b>(c)</b> US images show diffuse subcutaneous edema with increased vascularity (arrow in <b>c</b>). <i>Lt</i> = left, <i>Rt</i> = right. <b>(d)</b> Photomicrographs of the specimen obtained at core biopsy show dense patchy infiltrates of small to medium lymphoid cells, with scant to moderate pale cytoplasm, irregular nuclear contours, and coarse chromatin. (Hematoxylin-eosin [H-E] stain; original magnifications, ×20 [left] and ×100 [right].) <b>(e–g)</b> Photomicrographs obtained after immunohistochemical (IHC) staining with CD20 <b>(e)</b>, Ki-67 <b>(f)</b>, and kappa <b>(g)</b> stains show positivity for CD20, BCL-2, and BCL-6 B-cells and a Ki-67 proliferation index of 5%. (Original magnification of <b>e</b> and <b>f</b>, ×100; original magnification of <b>g</b>, ×400.) Cyclin D1 is negative, and flow cytometry reveals monotypic (κ+) B-cells. The results of the pathologic examination confirmed SBL (splenic marginal-zone lymphoma).<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2019180097&amp;id=fig3a">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig3b" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2019180097/asset/images/large/rg.2019180097.fig3b.jpeg" height="835" width="1382" aria-labelledby="fig3b" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 3b</span>. SBL in a 68-year-old woman with a history of splenomegaly who underwent screening mammography. <b>(a)</b> Bilateral MLO mammograms reveal diffuse bilateral skin (blue arrows) and trabecular (yellow arrows) thickening, with no mass. <i>Lt</i> = left, <i>Rt</i> = right. <b>(b, c)</b> Gray-scale <b>(b)</b> and color Doppler flow <b>(c)</b> US images show diffuse subcutaneous edema with increased vascularity (arrow in <b>c</b>). <i>Lt</i> = left, <i>Rt</i> = right. <b>(d)</b> Photomicrographs of the specimen obtained at core biopsy show dense patchy infiltrates of small to medium lymphoid cells, with scant to moderate pale cytoplasm, irregular nuclear contours, and coarse chromatin. (Hematoxylin-eosin [H-E] stain; original magnifications, ×20 [left] and ×100 [right].) <b>(e–g)</b> Photomicrographs obtained after immunohistochemical (IHC) staining with CD20 <b>(e)</b>, Ki-67 <b>(f)</b>, and kappa <b>(g)</b> stains show positivity for CD20, BCL-2, and BCL-6 B-cells and a Ki-67 proliferation index of 5%. (Original magnification of <b>e</b> and <b>f</b>, ×100; original magnification of <b>g</b>, ×400.) Cyclin D1 is negative, and flow cytometry reveals monotypic (κ+) B-cells. The results of the pathologic examination confirmed SBL (splenic marginal-zone lymphoma).<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2019180097&amp;id=fig3b">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig3c" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2019180097/asset/images/large/rg.2019180097.fig3c.jpeg" height="740" width="1388" aria-labelledby="fig3c" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 3c</span>. SBL in a 68-year-old woman with a history of splenomegaly who underwent screening mammography. <b>(a)</b> Bilateral MLO mammograms reveal diffuse bilateral skin (blue arrows) and trabecular (yellow arrows) thickening, with no mass. <i>Lt</i> = left, <i>Rt</i> = right. <b>(b, c)</b> Gray-scale <b>(b)</b> and color Doppler flow <b>(c)</b> US images show diffuse subcutaneous edema with increased vascularity (arrow in <b>c</b>). <i>Lt</i> = left, <i>Rt</i> = right. <b>(d)</b> Photomicrographs of the specimen obtained at core biopsy show dense patchy infiltrates of small to medium lymphoid cells, with scant to moderate pale cytoplasm, irregular nuclear contours, and coarse chromatin. (Hematoxylin-eosin [H-E] stain; original magnifications, ×20 [left] and ×100 [right].) <b>(e–g)</b> Photomicrographs obtained after immunohistochemical (IHC) staining with CD20 <b>(e)</b>, Ki-67 <b>(f)</b>, and kappa <b>(g)</b> stains show positivity for CD20, BCL-2, and BCL-6 B-cells and a Ki-67 proliferation index of 5%. (Original magnification of <b>e</b> and <b>f</b>, ×100; original magnification of <b>g</b>, ×400.) Cyclin D1 is negative, and flow cytometry reveals monotypic (κ+) B-cells. The results of the pathologic examination confirmed SBL (splenic marginal-zone lymphoma).<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2019180097&amp;id=fig3c">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig3d" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2019180097/asset/images/large/rg.2019180097.fig3d.jpeg" height="921" width="1920" aria-labelledby="fig3d" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 3d</span>. SBL in a 68-year-old woman with a history of splenomegaly who underwent screening mammography. <b>(a)</b> Bilateral MLO mammograms reveal diffuse bilateral skin (blue arrows) and trabecular (yellow arrows) thickening, with no mass. <i>Lt</i> = left, <i>Rt</i> = right. <b>(b, c)</b> Gray-scale <b>(b)</b> and color Doppler flow <b>(c)</b> US images show diffuse subcutaneous edema with increased vascularity (arrow in <b>c</b>). <i>Lt</i> = left, <i>Rt</i> = right. <b>(d)</b> Photomicrographs of the specimen obtained at core biopsy show dense patchy infiltrates of small to medium lymphoid cells, with scant to moderate pale cytoplasm, irregular nuclear contours, and coarse chromatin. (Hematoxylin-eosin [H-E] stain; original magnifications, ×20 [left] and ×100 [right].) <b>(e–g)</b> Photomicrographs obtained after immunohistochemical (IHC) staining with CD20 <b>(e)</b>, Ki-67 <b>(f)</b>, and kappa <b>(g)</b> stains show positivity for CD20, BCL-2, and BCL-6 B-cells and a Ki-67 proliferation index of 5%. (Original magnification of <b>e</b> and <b>f</b>, ×100; original magnification of <b>g</b>, ×400.) Cyclin D1 is negative, and flow cytometry reveals monotypic (κ+) B-cells. The results of the pathologic examination confirmed SBL (splenic marginal-zone lymphoma).<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2019180097&amp;id=fig3d">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig3e" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2019180097/asset/images/large/rg.2019180097.fig3e.jpeg" height="921" width="1229" aria-labelledby="fig3e" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 3e</span>. SBL in a 68-year-old woman with a history of splenomegaly who underwent screening mammography. <b>(a)</b> Bilateral MLO mammograms reveal diffuse bilateral skin (blue arrows) and trabecular (yellow arrows) thickening, with no mass. <i>Lt</i> = left, <i>Rt</i> = right. <b>(b, c)</b> Gray-scale <b>(b)</b> and color Doppler flow <b>(c)</b> US images show diffuse subcutaneous edema with increased vascularity (arrow in <b>c</b>). <i>Lt</i> = left, <i>Rt</i> = right. <b>(d)</b> Photomicrographs of the specimen obtained at core biopsy show dense patchy infiltrates of small to medium lymphoid cells, with scant to moderate pale cytoplasm, irregular nuclear contours, and coarse chromatin. (Hematoxylin-eosin [H-E] stain; original magnifications, ×20 [left] and ×100 [right].) <b>(e–g)</b> Photomicrographs obtained after immunohistochemical (IHC) staining with CD20 <b>(e)</b>, Ki-67 <b>(f)</b>, and kappa <b>(g)</b> stains show positivity for CD20, BCL-2, and BCL-6 B-cells and a Ki-67 proliferation index of 5%. (Original magnification of <b>e</b> and <b>f</b>, ×100; original magnification of <b>g</b>, ×400.) Cyclin D1 is negative, and flow cytometry reveals monotypic (κ+) B-cells. The results of the pathologic examination confirmed SBL (splenic marginal-zone lymphoma).<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2019180097&amp;id=fig3e">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig3f" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2019180097/asset/images/large/rg.2019180097.fig3f.jpeg" height="1031" width="1376" aria-labelledby="fig3f" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 3f</span>. SBL in a 68-year-old woman with a history of splenomegaly who underwent screening mammography. <b>(a)</b> Bilateral MLO mammograms reveal diffuse bilateral skin (blue arrows) and trabecular (yellow arrows) thickening, with no mass. <i>Lt</i> = left, <i>Rt</i> = right. <b>(b, c)</b> Gray-scale <b>(b)</b> and color Doppler flow <b>(c)</b> US images show diffuse subcutaneous edema with increased vascularity (arrow in <b>c</b>). <i>Lt</i> = left, <i>Rt</i> = right. <b>(d)</b> Photomicrographs of the specimen obtained at core biopsy show dense patchy infiltrates of small to medium lymphoid cells, with scant to moderate pale cytoplasm, irregular nuclear contours, and coarse chromatin. (Hematoxylin-eosin [H-E] stain; original magnifications, ×20 [left] and ×100 [right].) <b>(e–g)</b> Photomicrographs obtained after immunohistochemical (IHC) staining with CD20 <b>(e)</b>, Ki-67 <b>(f)</b>, and kappa <b>(g)</b> stains show positivity for CD20, BCL-2, and BCL-6 B-cells and a Ki-67 proliferation index of 5%. (Original magnification of <b>e</b> and <b>f</b>, ×100; original magnification of <b>g</b>, ×400.) Cyclin D1 is negative, and flow cytometry reveals monotypic (κ+) B-cells. The results of the pathologic examination confirmed SBL (splenic marginal-zone lymphoma).<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2019180097&amp;id=fig3f">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig3g" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2019180097/asset/images/large/rg.2019180097.fig3g.jpeg" height="1031" width="1376" aria-labelledby="fig3g" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 3g</span>. SBL in a 68-year-old woman with a history of splenomegaly who underwent screening mammography. <b>(a)</b> Bilateral MLO mammograms reveal diffuse bilateral skin (blue arrows) and trabecular (yellow arrows) thickening, with no mass. <i>Lt</i> = left, <i>Rt</i> = right. <b>(b, c)</b> Gray-scale <b>(b)</b> and color Doppler flow <b>(c)</b> US images show diffuse subcutaneous edema with increased vascularity (arrow in <b>c</b>). <i>Lt</i> = left, <i>Rt</i> = right. <b>(d)</b> Photomicrographs of the specimen obtained at core biopsy show dense patchy infiltrates of small to medium lymphoid cells, with scant to moderate pale cytoplasm, irregular nuclear contours, and coarse chromatin. (Hematoxylin-eosin [H-E] stain; original magnifications, ×20 [left] and ×100 [right].) <b>(e–g)</b> Photomicrographs obtained after immunohistochemical (IHC) staining with CD20 <b>(e)</b>, Ki-67 <b>(f)</b>, and kappa <b>(g)</b> stains show positivity for CD20, BCL-2, and BCL-6 B-cells and a Ki-67 proliferation index of 5%. (Original magnification of <b>e</b> and <b>f</b>, ×100; original magnification of <b>g</b>, ×400.) Cyclin D1 is negative, and flow cytometry reveals monotypic (κ+) B-cells. The results of the pathologic examination confirmed SBL (splenic marginal-zone lymphoma).<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2019180097&amp;id=fig3g">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig4a" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2019180097/asset/images/large/rg.2019180097.fig4a.jpeg" height="1749" width="1182" aria-labelledby="fig4a" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 4a</span>. Primary NHL in a 76-year-old woman with a palpable lump. <b>(a, b)</b> CC <b>(a)</b> and MLO <b>(b)</b> mammograms of the left <i>(LT)</i> breast obtained 6 months before clinical presentation show no evidence of malignancy. <b>(c, d)</b> Diagnostic CC <b>(c)</b> and mediolateral (ML) <b>(d)</b> mammograms obtained 6 months later show an oval circumscribed mass with high density in the anterior upper outer left <i>(LT)</i> breast. <b>(e)</b> Diagnostic color Doppler flow US image shows an oval mass with mixed echogenicity, posterior acoustic enhancement, and internal vascularity. Core biopsy was performed (not shown), and the results confirmed primary NHL. <b>(f)</b> Axial PET/CT image obtained prior to treatment with chemotherapy (<i>Pre-Chemo)</i> shows a corresponding left breast mass with high FDG avidity. <b>(g)</b> Axial PET/CT image obtained 3 months after the completion of chemotherapy (<i>Post-Chemo)</i> shows a favorable response to treatment, with FDG uptake returning to background levels.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2019180097&amp;id=fig4a">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig4b" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2019180097/asset/images/large/rg.2019180097.fig4b.jpeg" height="1649" width="1182" aria-labelledby="fig4b" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 4b</span>. Primary NHL in a 76-year-old woman with a palpable lump. <b>(a, b)</b> CC <b>(a)</b> and MLO <b>(b)</b> mammograms of the left <i>(LT)</i> breast obtained 6 months before clinical presentation show no evidence of malignancy. <b>(c, d)</b> Diagnostic CC <b>(c)</b> and mediolateral (ML) <b>(d)</b> mammograms obtained 6 months later show an oval circumscribed mass with high density in the anterior upper outer left <i>(LT)</i> breast. <b>(e)</b> Diagnostic color Doppler flow US image shows an oval mass with mixed echogenicity, posterior acoustic enhancement, and internal vascularity. Core biopsy was performed (not shown), and the results confirmed primary NHL. <b>(f)</b> Axial PET/CT image obtained prior to treatment with chemotherapy (<i>Pre-Chemo)</i> shows a corresponding left breast mass with high FDG avidity. <b>(g)</b> Axial PET/CT image obtained 3 months after the completion of chemotherapy (<i>Post-Chemo)</i> shows a favorable response to treatment, with FDG uptake returning to background levels.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2019180097&amp;id=fig4b">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig4c" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2019180097/asset/images/large/rg.2019180097.fig4c.jpeg" height="1628" width="1032" aria-labelledby="fig4c" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 4c</span>. Primary NHL in a 76-year-old woman with a palpable lump. <b>(a, b)</b> CC <b>(a)</b> and MLO <b>(b)</b> mammograms of the left <i>(LT)</i> breast obtained 6 months before clinical presentation show no evidence of malignancy. <b>(c, d)</b> Diagnostic CC <b>(c)</b> and mediolateral (ML) <b>(d)</b> mammograms obtained 6 months later show an oval circumscribed mass with high density in the anterior upper outer left <i>(LT)</i> breast. <b>(e)</b> Diagnostic color Doppler flow US image shows an oval mass with mixed echogenicity, posterior acoustic enhancement, and internal vascularity. Core biopsy was performed (not shown), and the results confirmed primary NHL. <b>(f)</b> Axial PET/CT image obtained prior to treatment with chemotherapy (<i>Pre-Chemo)</i> shows a corresponding left breast mass with high FDG avidity. <b>(g)</b> Axial PET/CT image obtained 3 months after the completion of chemotherapy (<i>Post-Chemo)</i> shows a favorable response to treatment, with FDG uptake returning to background levels.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2019180097&amp;id=fig4c">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig4d" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2019180097/asset/images/large/rg.2019180097.fig4d.jpeg" height="1777" width="1032" aria-labelledby="fig4d" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 4d</span>. Primary NHL in a 76-year-old woman with a palpable lump. <b>(a, b)</b> CC <b>(a)</b> and MLO <b>(b)</b> mammograms of the left <i>(LT)</i> breast obtained 6 months before clinical presentation show no evidence of malignancy. <b>(c, d)</b> Diagnostic CC <b>(c)</b> and mediolateral (ML) <b>(d)</b> mammograms obtained 6 months later show an oval circumscribed mass with high density in the anterior upper outer left <i>(LT)</i> breast. <b>(e)</b> Diagnostic color Doppler flow US image shows an oval mass with mixed echogenicity, posterior acoustic enhancement, and internal vascularity. Core biopsy was performed (not shown), and the results confirmed primary NHL. <b>(f)</b> Axial PET/CT image obtained prior to treatment with chemotherapy (<i>Pre-Chemo)</i> shows a corresponding left breast mass with high FDG avidity. <b>(g)</b> Axial PET/CT image obtained 3 months after the completion of chemotherapy (<i>Post-Chemo)</i> shows a favorable response to treatment, with FDG uptake returning to background levels.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2019180097&amp;id=fig4d">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig4e" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2019180097/asset/images/large/rg.2019180097.fig4e.jpeg" height="701" width="1079" aria-labelledby="fig4e" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 4e</span>. Primary NHL in a 76-year-old woman with a palpable lump. <b>(a, b)</b> CC <b>(a)</b> and MLO <b>(b)</b> mammograms of the left <i>(LT)</i> breast obtained 6 months before clinical presentation show no evidence of malignancy. <b>(c, d)</b> Diagnostic CC <b>(c)</b> and mediolateral (ML) <b>(d)</b> mammograms obtained 6 months later show an oval circumscribed mass with high density in the anterior upper outer left <i>(LT)</i> breast. <b>(e)</b> Diagnostic color Doppler flow US image shows an oval mass with mixed echogenicity, posterior acoustic enhancement, and internal vascularity. Core biopsy was performed (not shown), and the results confirmed primary NHL. <b>(f)</b> Axial PET/CT image obtained prior to treatment with chemotherapy (<i>Pre-Chemo)</i> shows a corresponding left breast mass with high FDG avidity. <b>(g)</b> Axial PET/CT image obtained 3 months after the completion of chemotherapy (<i>Post-Chemo)</i> shows a favorable response to treatment, with FDG uptake returning to background levels.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2019180097&amp;id=fig4e">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig4f" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2019180097/asset/images/large/rg.2019180097.fig4f.jpeg" height="1174" width="1079" aria-labelledby="fig4f" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 4f</span>. Primary NHL in a 76-year-old woman with a palpable lump. <b>(a, b)</b> CC <b>(a)</b> and MLO <b>(b)</b> mammograms of the left <i>(LT)</i> breast obtained 6 months before clinical presentation show no evidence of malignancy. <b>(c, d)</b> Diagnostic CC <b>(c)</b> and mediolateral (ML) <b>(d)</b> mammograms obtained 6 months later show an oval circumscribed mass with high density in the anterior upper outer left <i>(LT)</i> breast. <b>(e)</b> Diagnostic color Doppler flow US image shows an oval mass with mixed echogenicity, posterior acoustic enhancement, and internal vascularity. Core biopsy was performed (not shown), and the results confirmed primary NHL. <b>(f)</b> Axial PET/CT image obtained prior to treatment with chemotherapy (<i>Pre-Chemo)</i> shows a corresponding left breast mass with high FDG avidity. <b>(g)</b> Axial PET/CT image obtained 3 months after the completion of chemotherapy (<i>Post-Chemo)</i> shows a favorable response to treatment, with FDG uptake returning to background levels.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2019180097&amp;id=fig4f">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig4g" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2019180097/asset/images/large/rg.2019180097.fig4g.jpeg" height="1376" width="1079" aria-labelledby="fig4g" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 4g</span>. Primary NHL in a 76-year-old woman with a palpable lump. <b>(a, b)</b> CC <b>(a)</b> and MLO <b>(b)</b> mammograms of the left <i>(LT)</i> breast obtained 6 months before clinical presentation show no evidence of malignancy. <b>(c, d)</b> Diagnostic CC <b>(c)</b> and mediolateral (ML) <b>(d)</b> mammograms obtained 6 months later show an oval circumscribed mass with high density in the anterior upper outer left <i>(LT)</i> breast. <b>(e)</b> Diagnostic color Doppler flow US image shows an oval mass with mixed echogenicity, posterior acoustic enhancement, and internal vascularity. Core biopsy was performed (not shown), and the results confirmed primary NHL. <b>(f)</b> Axial PET/CT image obtained prior to treatment with chemotherapy (<i>Pre-Chemo)</i> shows a corresponding left breast mass with high FDG avidity. <b>(g)</b> Axial PET/CT image obtained 3 months after the completion of chemotherapy (<i>Post-Chemo)</i> shows a favorable response to treatment, with FDG uptake returning to background levels.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2019180097&amp;id=fig4g">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig5a" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2019180097/asset/images/large/rg.2019180097.fig5a.jpeg" height="909" width="1132" aria-labelledby="fig5a" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 5a</span>. SBL in a 63-year-old woman with a known history of lymphoma in remission who presented with palpable lumps 5 months after undergoing screening mammography, which was interpreted as negative. Gray-scale <b>(a)</b> and color Doppler flow <b>(b)</b> US images show lesion echogenicity, which is often hypoechoic or mixed, vascularity, posterior acoustic enhancement, and an echogenic rim.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2019180097&amp;id=fig5a">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig5b" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2019180097/asset/images/large/rg.2019180097.fig5b.jpeg" height="909" width="1121" aria-labelledby="fig5b" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 5b</span>. SBL in a 63-year-old woman with a known history of lymphoma in remission who presented with palpable lumps 5 months after undergoing screening mammography, which was interpreted as negative. Gray-scale <b>(a)</b> and color Doppler flow <b>(b)</b> US images show lesion echogenicity, which is often hypoechoic or mixed, vascularity, posterior acoustic enhancement, and an echogenic rim.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2019180097&amp;id=fig5b">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig6" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2019180097/asset/images/large/rg.2019180097.fig6.jpeg" height="1629" width="1800" aria-labelledby="fig6" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 6</span>. PBL (follicular subtype) confirmed by the results of a biopsy in a 57-year-old woman with a palpable lump. Axial MR image obtained for initial staging shows a heterogeneously enhancing oval mass (arrow) with irregular margins. MRI features of PBL are nonspecific and include a round or oval mass, areas of hypointensity or isointensity at T1-weighted imaging, areas of hyperintensity at T2-weighted imaging, and areas of enhancement with a type II kinetic curve.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2019180097&amp;id=fig6">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig7a" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2019180097/asset/images/large/rg.2019180097.fig7a.jpeg" height="2362" width="966" aria-labelledby="fig7a" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 7a</span>. PBL confirmed by the results of a biopsy in a 49-year-old woman who underwent PET/CT for a staging evaluation. FDG maximum intensity projection <b>(a)</b> and axial PET/CT <b>(b)</b> images show a single oval mass with high FDG avidity (arrow), a finding consistent with PBL. No additional ipsilateral, contralateral, or extramammary metastatic masses were identified.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2019180097&amp;id=fig7a">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig7b" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2019180097/asset/images/large/rg.2019180097.fig7b.jpeg" height="1274" width="1692" aria-labelledby="fig7b" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 7b</span>. PBL confirmed by the results of a biopsy in a 49-year-old woman who underwent PET/CT for a staging evaluation. FDG maximum intensity projection <b>(a)</b> and axial PET/CT <b>(b)</b> images show a single oval mass with high FDG avidity (arrow), a finding consistent with PBL. No additional ipsilateral, contralateral, or extramammary metastatic masses were identified.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2019180097&amp;id=fig7b">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig8a" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2019180097/asset/images/large/rg.2019180097.fig8a.jpeg" height="1825" width="1242" aria-labelledby="fig8a" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 8a</span>. PBL (follicular lymphoma) in a 38-year-old woman with a palpable lump. <b>(a–c)</b> CC <b>(a)</b> and MLO <b>(b)</b> mammograms and magnified <i>(Mag)</i> area of interest on the CC view <b>(c)</b> show an irregular indistinct high-density mass (arrow) in the lower inner left breast. <b>(d)</b> Gray-scale US image shows an oval heterogeneous mass (arrow) with mixed echogenicity. <b>(e)</b> Axial CT image shows an oval indistinct mass (arrow), which corresponds to the mass depicted at mammography. <b>(f)</b> Axial PET image shows the mass with heterogeneously high FDG avidity (arrow). The results of a pathologic examination confirmed primary follicular lymphoma.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2019180097&amp;id=fig8a">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig8b" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2019180097/asset/images/large/rg.2019180097.fig8b.jpeg" height="1825" width="1318" aria-labelledby="fig8b" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 8b</span>. PBL (follicular lymphoma) in a 38-year-old woman with a palpable lump. <b>(a–c)</b> CC <b>(a)</b> and MLO <b>(b)</b> mammograms and magnified <i>(Mag)</i> area of interest on the CC view <b>(c)</b> show an irregular indistinct high-density mass (arrow) in the lower inner left breast. <b>(d)</b> Gray-scale US image shows an oval heterogeneous mass (arrow) with mixed echogenicity. <b>(e)</b> Axial CT image shows an oval indistinct mass (arrow), which corresponds to the mass depicted at mammography. <b>(f)</b> Axial PET image shows the mass with heterogeneously high FDG avidity (arrow). The results of a pathologic examination confirmed primary follicular lymphoma.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2019180097&amp;id=fig8b">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig8c" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2019180097/asset/images/large/rg.2019180097.fig8c.jpeg" height="942" width="1136" aria-labelledby="fig8c" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 8c</span>. PBL (follicular lymphoma) in a 38-year-old woman with a palpable lump. <b>(a–c)</b> CC <b>(a)</b> and MLO <b>(b)</b> mammograms and magnified <i>(Mag)</i> area of interest on the CC view <b>(c)</b> show an irregular indistinct high-density mass (arrow) in the lower inner left breast. <b>(d)</b> Gray-scale US image shows an oval heterogeneous mass (arrow) with mixed echogenicity. <b>(e)</b> Axial CT image shows an oval indistinct mass (arrow), which corresponds to the mass depicted at mammography. <b>(f)</b> Axial PET image shows the mass with heterogeneously high FDG avidity (arrow). The results of a pathologic examination confirmed primary follicular lymphoma.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2019180097&amp;id=fig8c">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig8d" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2019180097/asset/images/large/rg.2019180097.fig8d.jpeg" height="842" width="1134" aria-labelledby="fig8d" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 8d</span>. PBL (follicular lymphoma) in a 38-year-old woman with a palpable lump. <b>(a–c)</b> CC <b>(a)</b> and MLO <b>(b)</b> mammograms and magnified <i>(Mag)</i> area of interest on the CC view <b>(c)</b> show an irregular indistinct high-density mass (arrow) in the lower inner left breast. <b>(d)</b> Gray-scale US image shows an oval heterogeneous mass (arrow) with mixed echogenicity. <b>(e)</b> Axial CT image shows an oval indistinct mass (arrow), which corresponds to the mass depicted at mammography. <b>(f)</b> Axial PET image shows the mass with heterogeneously high FDG avidity (arrow). The results of a pathologic examination confirmed primary follicular lymphoma.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2019180097&amp;id=fig8d">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig8e" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2019180097/asset/images/large/rg.2019180097.fig8e.jpeg" height="842" width="1224" aria-labelledby="fig8e" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 8e</span>. PBL (follicular lymphoma) in a 38-year-old woman with a palpable lump. <b>(a–c)</b> CC <b>(a)</b> and MLO <b>(b)</b> mammograms and magnified <i>(Mag)</i> area of interest on the CC view <b>(c)</b> show an irregular indistinct high-density mass (arrow) in the lower inner left breast. <b>(d)</b> Gray-scale US image shows an oval heterogeneous mass (arrow) with mixed echogenicity. <b>(e)</b> Axial CT image shows an oval indistinct mass (arrow), which corresponds to the mass depicted at mammography. <b>(f)</b> Axial PET image shows the mass with heterogeneously high FDG avidity (arrow). The results of a pathologic examination confirmed primary follicular lymphoma.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2019180097&amp;id=fig8e">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig8f" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2019180097/asset/images/large/rg.2019180097.fig8f.jpeg" height="842" width="1342" aria-labelledby="fig8f" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 8f</span>. PBL (follicular lymphoma) in a 38-year-old woman with a palpable lump. <b>(a–c)</b> CC <b>(a)</b> and MLO <b>(b)</b> mammograms and magnified <i>(Mag)</i> area of interest on the CC view <b>(c)</b> show an irregular indistinct high-density mass (arrow) in the lower inner left breast. <b>(d)</b> Gray-scale US image shows an oval heterogeneous mass (arrow) with mixed echogenicity. <b>(e)</b> Axial CT image shows an oval indistinct mass (arrow), which corresponds to the mass depicted at mammography. <b>(f)</b> Axial PET image shows the mass with heterogeneously high FDG avidity (arrow). The results of a pathologic examination confirmed primary follicular lymphoma.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2019180097&amp;id=fig8f">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig9a" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2019180097/asset/images/large/rg.2019180097.fig9a.jpeg" height="1691" width="1199" aria-labelledby="fig9a" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 9a</span>. Secondary DLBCL in a 68-year-old woman with a history of B-cell lymphoma in remission for 10 years who presented with a self-reported lump. <b>(a)</b> MLO mammogram shows a mass (arrows) with indistinct margins in the right upper breast, corresponding to a palpable BB marker. <b>(b)</b> Gray-scale US image shows a mixed-echogenicity mass (arrows). <b>(c)</b> Axial PET/CT image shows a highly FDG-avid right breast mass (red arrow) and internal mammary nodes (white arrow). <b>(d)</b> Sagittal MR image shows multiple heterogeneously enhancing masses (arrows), a finding consistent with multicentric disease. The constellation of findings is consistent with SBL, including manifesting in an older patient with a history of treated lymphoma, the presence of multiple breast lesions, mixed echogenicity depicted at US, and additional sites of extramammary metastatic disease (in this case, the internal mammary nodes). The results of a pathologic examination confirmed secondary DLBCL.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2019180097&amp;id=fig9a">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig9b" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2019180097/asset/images/large/rg.2019180097.fig9b.jpeg" height="1129" width="1423" aria-labelledby="fig9b" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 9b</span>. Secondary DLBCL in a 68-year-old woman with a history of B-cell lymphoma in remission for 10 years who presented with a self-reported lump. <b>(a)</b> MLO mammogram shows a mass (arrows) with indistinct margins in the right upper breast, corresponding to a palpable BB marker. <b>(b)</b> Gray-scale US image shows a mixed-echogenicity mass (arrows). <b>(c)</b> Axial PET/CT image shows a highly FDG-avid right breast mass (red arrow) and internal mammary nodes (white arrow). <b>(d)</b> Sagittal MR image shows multiple heterogeneously enhancing masses (arrows), a finding consistent with multicentric disease. The constellation of findings is consistent with SBL, including manifesting in an older patient with a history of treated lymphoma, the presence of multiple breast lesions, mixed echogenicity depicted at US, and additional sites of extramammary metastatic disease (in this case, the internal mammary nodes). The results of a pathologic examination confirmed secondary DLBCL.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2019180097&amp;id=fig9b">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig9c" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2019180097/asset/images/large/rg.2019180097.fig9c.jpeg" height="1129" width="1326" aria-labelledby="fig9c" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 9c</span>. Secondary DLBCL in a 68-year-old woman with a history of B-cell lymphoma in remission for 10 years who presented with a self-reported lump. <b>(a)</b> MLO mammogram shows a mass (arrows) with indistinct margins in the right upper breast, corresponding to a palpable BB marker. <b>(b)</b> Gray-scale US image shows a mixed-echogenicity mass (arrows). <b>(c)</b> Axial PET/CT image shows a highly FDG-avid right breast mass (red arrow) and internal mammary nodes (white arrow). <b>(d)</b> Sagittal MR image shows multiple heterogeneously enhancing masses (arrows), a finding consistent with multicentric disease. The constellation of findings is consistent with SBL, including manifesting in an older patient with a history of treated lymphoma, the presence of multiple breast lesions, mixed echogenicity depicted at US, and additional sites of extramammary metastatic disease (in this case, the internal mammary nodes). The results of a pathologic examination confirmed secondary DLBCL.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2019180097&amp;id=fig9c">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig9d" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2019180097/asset/images/large/rg.2019180097.fig9d.jpeg" height="1691" width="1553" aria-labelledby="fig9d" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 9d</span>. Secondary DLBCL in a 68-year-old woman with a history of B-cell lymphoma in remission for 10 years who presented with a self-reported lump. <b>(a)</b> MLO mammogram shows a mass (arrows) with indistinct margins in the right upper breast, corresponding to a palpable BB marker. <b>(b)</b> Gray-scale US image shows a mixed-echogenicity mass (arrows). <b>(c)</b> Axial PET/CT image shows a highly FDG-avid right breast mass (red arrow) and internal mammary nodes (white arrow). <b>(d)</b> Sagittal MR image shows multiple heterogeneously enhancing masses (arrows), a finding consistent with multicentric disease. The constellation of findings is consistent with SBL, including manifesting in an older patient with a history of treated lymphoma, the presence of multiple breast lesions, mixed echogenicity depicted at US, and additional sites of extramammary metastatic disease (in this case, the internal mammary nodes). The results of a pathologic examination confirmed secondary DLBCL.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2019180097&amp;id=fig9d">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig10a" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2019180097/asset/images/large/rg.2019180097.fig10a.jpeg" height="2099" width="1089" aria-labelledby="fig10a" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 10a</span>. Progressive left breast enlargement over 3 months in a 44-year-old woman who underwent cosmetic breast augmentation 7 years earlier. <b>(a, b)</b> MLO <b>(a)</b> and ML <b>(b)</b> mammograms show a circumferential abnormal asymmetry (yellow arrow) around the subglandular silicone implant (green arrow). <b>(c)</b> US image shows a peri-implant complex cyst and/or collection with debris (implant not depicted). <b>(d)</b> US image obtained during US-guided fine-needle aspiration shows the needle (arrow) within the complex cyst and/or collection. The results confirmed a definitive diagnosis of lymphoma. <b>(e)</b> Axial contrast material–enhanced CT <i>(Ax CT C+)</i> image of the chest was obtained unrelated to the patient’s lymphoma evaluation and showed a fluid collection and/or effusion surrounding the implant, with subtle enhancing foci along the left chest wall (arrow). The results of a pathologic examination confirmed BIAALCL.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2019180097&amp;id=fig10a">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig10b" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2019180097/asset/images/large/rg.2019180097.fig10b.jpeg" height="2097" width="1063" aria-labelledby="fig10b" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 10b</span>. Progressive left breast enlargement over 3 months in a 44-year-old woman who underwent cosmetic breast augmentation 7 years earlier. <b>(a, b)</b> MLO <b>(a)</b> and ML <b>(b)</b> mammograms show a circumferential abnormal asymmetry (yellow arrow) around the subglandular silicone implant (green arrow). <b>(c)</b> US image shows a peri-implant complex cyst and/or collection with debris (implant not depicted). <b>(d)</b> US image obtained during US-guided fine-needle aspiration shows the needle (arrow) within the complex cyst and/or collection. The results confirmed a definitive diagnosis of lymphoma. <b>(e)</b> Axial contrast material–enhanced CT <i>(Ax CT C+)</i> image of the chest was obtained unrelated to the patient’s lymphoma evaluation and showed a fluid collection and/or effusion surrounding the implant, with subtle enhancing foci along the left chest wall (arrow). The results of a pathologic examination confirmed BIAALCL.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2019180097&amp;id=fig10b">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig10c" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2019180097/asset/images/large/rg.2019180097.fig10c.jpeg" height="1035" width="1552" aria-labelledby="fig10c" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 10c</span>. Progressive left breast enlargement over 3 months in a 44-year-old woman who underwent cosmetic breast augmentation 7 years earlier. <b>(a, b)</b> MLO <b>(a)</b> and ML <b>(b)</b> mammograms show a circumferential abnormal asymmetry (yellow arrow) around the subglandular silicone implant (green arrow). <b>(c)</b> US image shows a peri-implant complex cyst and/or collection with debris (implant not depicted). <b>(d)</b> US image obtained during US-guided fine-needle aspiration shows the needle (arrow) within the complex cyst and/or collection. The results confirmed a definitive diagnosis of lymphoma. <b>(e)</b> Axial contrast material–enhanced CT <i>(Ax CT C+)</i> image of the chest was obtained unrelated to the patient’s lymphoma evaluation and showed a fluid collection and/or effusion surrounding the implant, with subtle enhancing foci along the left chest wall (arrow). The results of a pathologic examination confirmed BIAALCL.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2019180097&amp;id=fig10c">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig10d" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2019180097/asset/images/large/rg.2019180097.fig10d.jpeg" height="913" width="1548" aria-labelledby="fig10d" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 10d</span>. Progressive left breast enlargement over 3 months in a 44-year-old woman who underwent cosmetic breast augmentation 7 years earlier. <b>(a, b)</b> MLO <b>(a)</b> and ML <b>(b)</b> mammograms show a circumferential abnormal asymmetry (yellow arrow) around the subglandular silicone implant (green arrow). <b>(c)</b> US image shows a peri-implant complex cyst and/or collection with debris (implant not depicted). <b>(d)</b> US image obtained during US-guided fine-needle aspiration shows the needle (arrow) within the complex cyst and/or collection. The results confirmed a definitive diagnosis of lymphoma. <b>(e)</b> Axial contrast material–enhanced CT <i>(Ax CT C+)</i> image of the chest was obtained unrelated to the patient’s lymphoma evaluation and showed a fluid collection and/or effusion surrounding the implant, with subtle enhancing foci along the left chest wall (arrow). The results of a pathologic examination confirmed BIAALCL.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2019180097&amp;id=fig10d">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig10e" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2019180097/asset/images/large/rg.2019180097.fig10e.jpeg" height="766" width="1801" aria-labelledby="fig10e" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 10e</span>. Progressive left breast enlargement over 3 months in a 44-year-old woman who underwent cosmetic breast augmentation 7 years earlier. <b>(a, b)</b> MLO <b>(a)</b> and ML <b>(b)</b> mammograms show a circumferential abnormal asymmetry (yellow arrow) around the subglandular silicone implant (green arrow). <b>(c)</b> US image shows a peri-implant complex cyst and/or collection with debris (implant not depicted). <b>(d)</b> US image obtained during US-guided fine-needle aspiration shows the needle (arrow) within the complex cyst and/or collection. The results confirmed a definitive diagnosis of lymphoma. <b>(e)</b> Axial contrast material–enhanced CT <i>(Ax CT C+)</i> image of the chest was obtained unrelated to the patient’s lymphoma evaluation and showed a fluid collection and/or effusion surrounding the implant, with subtle enhancing foci along the left chest wall (arrow). The results of a pathologic examination confirmed BIAALCL.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2019180097&amp;id=fig10e">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig11a" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2019180097/asset/images/large/rg.2019180097.fig11a.jpeg" height="1843" width="862" aria-labelledby="fig11a" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 11a</span>. Primary B-cell NHL in a 67-year-old woman who underwent cosmetic breast augmentation and presented with a palpable lump. <b>(a, b)</b> MLO <b>(a)</b> and CC <b>(b)</b> mammograms show a partially depicted oval high-density circumscribed mass (arrow) adjacent to the prepectoral silicone implant. <b>(c)</b> Gray-scale US image shows an oval mass (arrow) with mixed echogenicity abutting the implant. <b>(d)</b> Axial PET image shows a mass with high FDG avidity (arrow). <b>(e–g)</b> Axial contrast-enhanced subtraction <i>(Ax Sub)</i> <b>(e)</b>, sagittal short-τ inversion-recovery <i>(STIR)</i> silicone-suppressed <i>(Silicone Sup)</i> <b>(f)</b>, and axial T2-weighted <i>(Ax T2)</i> <b>(g)</b> MR images show a T2-isointense mass with heterogeneous enhancement (arrow in <b>e</b>) separate from the implant, which is not silicone containing (eg, the mass does not suppress at silicone suppression imaging, as does the silicone implant).<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2019180097&amp;id=fig11a">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig11b" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2019180097/asset/images/large/rg.2019180097.fig11b.jpeg" height="1843" width="892" aria-labelledby="fig11b" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 11b</span>. Primary B-cell NHL in a 67-year-old woman who underwent cosmetic breast augmentation and presented with a palpable lump. <b>(a, b)</b> MLO <b>(a)</b> and CC <b>(b)</b> mammograms show a partially depicted oval high-density circumscribed mass (arrow) adjacent to the prepectoral silicone implant. <b>(c)</b> Gray-scale US image shows an oval mass (arrow) with mixed echogenicity abutting the implant. <b>(d)</b> Axial PET image shows a mass with high FDG avidity (arrow). <b>(e–g)</b> Axial contrast-enhanced subtraction <i>(Ax Sub)</i> <b>(e)</b>, sagittal short-τ inversion-recovery <i>(STIR)</i> silicone-suppressed <i>(Silicone Sup)</i> <b>(f)</b>, and axial T2-weighted <i>(Ax T2)</i> <b>(g)</b> MR images show a T2-isointense mass with heterogeneous enhancement (arrow in <b>e</b>) separate from the implant, which is not silicone containing (eg, the mass does not suppress at silicone suppression imaging, as does the silicone implant).<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2019180097&amp;id=fig11b">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig11c" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2019180097/asset/images/large/rg.2019180097.fig11c.jpeg" height="922" width="1544" aria-labelledby="fig11c" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 11c</span>. Primary B-cell NHL in a 67-year-old woman who underwent cosmetic breast augmentation and presented with a palpable lump. <b>(a, b)</b> MLO <b>(a)</b> and CC <b>(b)</b> mammograms show a partially depicted oval high-density circumscribed mass (arrow) adjacent to the prepectoral silicone implant. <b>(c)</b> Gray-scale US image shows an oval mass (arrow) with mixed echogenicity abutting the implant. <b>(d)</b> Axial PET image shows a mass with high FDG avidity (arrow). <b>(e–g)</b> Axial contrast-enhanced subtraction <i>(Ax Sub)</i> <b>(e)</b>, sagittal short-τ inversion-recovery <i>(STIR)</i> silicone-suppressed <i>(Silicone Sup)</i> <b>(f)</b>, and axial T2-weighted <i>(Ax T2)</i> <b>(g)</b> MR images show a T2-isointense mass with heterogeneous enhancement (arrow in <b>e</b>) separate from the implant, which is not silicone containing (eg, the mass does not suppress at silicone suppression imaging, as does the silicone implant).<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2019180097&amp;id=fig11c">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig11d" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2019180097/asset/images/large/rg.2019180097.fig11d.jpeg" height="773" width="1544" aria-labelledby="fig11d" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 11d</span>. Primary B-cell NHL in a 67-year-old woman who underwent cosmetic breast augmentation and presented with a palpable lump. <b>(a, b)</b> MLO <b>(a)</b> and CC <b>(b)</b> mammograms show a partially depicted oval high-density circumscribed mass (arrow) adjacent to the prepectoral silicone implant. <b>(c)</b> Gray-scale US image shows an oval mass (arrow) with mixed echogenicity abutting the implant. <b>(d)</b> Axial PET image shows a mass with high FDG avidity (arrow). <b>(e–g)</b> Axial contrast-enhanced subtraction <i>(Ax Sub)</i> <b>(e)</b>, sagittal short-τ inversion-recovery <i>(STIR)</i> silicone-suppressed <i>(Silicone Sup)</i> <b>(f)</b>, and axial T2-weighted <i>(Ax T2)</i> <b>(g)</b> MR images show a T2-isointense mass with heterogeneous enhancement (arrow in <b>e</b>) separate from the implant, which is not silicone containing (eg, the mass does not suppress at silicone suppression imaging, as does the silicone implant).<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2019180097&amp;id=fig11d">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig11e" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2019180097/asset/images/large/rg.2019180097.fig11e.jpeg" height="1538" width="1007" aria-labelledby="fig11e" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 11e</span>. Primary B-cell NHL in a 67-year-old woman who underwent cosmetic breast augmentation and presented with a palpable lump. <b>(a, b)</b> MLO <b>(a)</b> and CC <b>(b)</b> mammograms show a partially depicted oval high-density circumscribed mass (arrow) adjacent to the prepectoral silicone implant. <b>(c)</b> Gray-scale US image shows an oval mass (arrow) with mixed echogenicity abutting the implant. <b>(d)</b> Axial PET image shows a mass with high FDG avidity (arrow). <b>(e–g)</b> Axial contrast-enhanced subtraction <i>(Ax Sub)</i> <b>(e)</b>, sagittal short-τ inversion-recovery <i>(STIR)</i> silicone-suppressed <i>(Silicone Sup)</i> <b>(f)</b>, and axial T2-weighted <i>(Ax T2)</i> <b>(g)</b> MR images show a T2-isointense mass with heterogeneous enhancement (arrow in <b>e</b>) separate from the implant, which is not silicone containing (eg, the mass does not suppress at silicone suppression imaging, as does the silicone implant).<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2019180097&amp;id=fig11e">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig11f" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2019180097/asset/images/large/rg.2019180097.fig11f.jpeg" height="1532" width="1182" aria-labelledby="fig11f" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 11f</span>. Primary B-cell NHL in a 67-year-old woman who underwent cosmetic breast augmentation and presented with a palpable lump. <b>(a, b)</b> MLO <b>(a)</b> and CC <b>(b)</b> mammograms show a partially depicted oval high-density circumscribed mass (arrow) adjacent to the prepectoral silicone implant. <b>(c)</b> Gray-scale US image shows an oval mass (arrow) with mixed echogenicity abutting the implant. <b>(d)</b> Axial PET image shows a mass with high FDG avidity (arrow). <b>(e–g)</b> Axial contrast-enhanced subtraction <i>(Ax Sub)</i> <b>(e)</b>, sagittal short-τ inversion-recovery <i>(STIR)</i> silicone-suppressed <i>(Silicone Sup)</i> <b>(f)</b>, and axial T2-weighted <i>(Ax T2)</i> <b>(g)</b> MR images show a T2-isointense mass with heterogeneous enhancement (arrow in <b>e</b>) separate from the implant, which is not silicone containing (eg, the mass does not suppress at silicone suppression imaging, as does the silicone implant).<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2019180097&amp;id=fig11f">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig11g" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2019180097/asset/images/large/rg.2019180097.fig11g.jpeg" height="1532" width="1114" aria-labelledby="fig11g" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 11g</span>. Primary B-cell NHL in a 67-year-old woman who underwent cosmetic breast augmentation and presented with a palpable lump. <b>(a, b)</b> MLO <b>(a)</b> and CC <b>(b)</b> mammograms show a partially depicted oval high-density circumscribed mass (arrow) adjacent to the prepectoral silicone implant. <b>(c)</b> Gray-scale US image shows an oval mass (arrow) with mixed echogenicity abutting the implant. <b>(d)</b> Axial PET image shows a mass with high FDG avidity (arrow). <b>(e–g)</b> Axial contrast-enhanced subtraction <i>(Ax Sub)</i> <b>(e)</b>, sagittal short-τ inversion-recovery <i>(STIR)</i> silicone-suppressed <i>(Silicone Sup)</i> <b>(f)</b>, and axial T2-weighted <i>(Ax T2)</i> <b>(g)</b> MR images show a T2-isointense mass with heterogeneous enhancement (arrow in <b>e</b>) separate from the implant, which is not silicone containing (eg, the mass does not suppress at silicone suppression imaging, as does the silicone implant).<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2019180097&amp;id=fig11g">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig12" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2019180097/asset/images/large/rg.2019180097.fig12.jpeg" height="1530" width="3600" aria-labelledby="fig12" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 12</span>. Radiology-pathology collaborative protocol used for suspected breast lymphoma at our institution. Flowchart shows the protocol for each biopsy technique and corresponding pathologic examination at our institution. While core-needle biopsy is the standard for tissue sampling of the breast and axilla, fine-needle aspiration can be performed per the policy established by an institution-specific collaboration between the radiology and pathology departments. When core biopsy is performed, at least five specimens should be acquired, per the protocol at our institution. With fine-needle aspiration, our institutional protocol recommends that at least four passes be obtained.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2019180097&amp;id=fig12">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig13" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2019180097/asset/images/large/rg.2019180097.fig13.jpeg" height="3040" width="1709" aria-labelledby="fig13" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 13</span>. Chart with photograph insets of pathology fixative containers shows the pathology fixatives and specimen media used at our institution, as indicated in the flowchart (<a href="#fig12">Fig 12</a>).<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2019180097&amp;id=fig13">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig14a" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2019180097/asset/images/large/rg.2019180097.fig14a.jpeg" height="1842" width="1567" aria-labelledby="fig14a" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 14a</span>. Cytologic difference between follicular breast lymphoma and invasive ductal carcinoma. <b>(a)</b> Photomicrograph shows dispersed single cells (arrows), a finding consistent with follicular lymphoma. (H-E stain; original magnification, ×400.) <b>(b)</b> Photomicrograph shows cohesive three-dimensional groups of tumor cells containing mucin vacuoles (arrows), a hallmark finding of adenocarcinoma. (Papanicolaou stain; original magnification, ×400.) Rapid interpretation of the results of cytology samples quickly allows for differentiation between these neoplasms.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2019180097&amp;id=fig14a">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig14b" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2019180097/asset/images/large/rg.2019180097.fig14b.jpeg" height="1842" width="1573" aria-labelledby="fig14b" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 14b</span>. Cytologic difference between follicular breast lymphoma and invasive ductal carcinoma. <b>(a)</b> Photomicrograph shows dispersed single cells (arrows), a finding consistent with follicular lymphoma. (H-E stain; original magnification, ×400.) <b>(b)</b> Photomicrograph shows cohesive three-dimensional groups of tumor cells containing mucin vacuoles (arrows), a hallmark finding of adenocarcinoma. (Papanicolaou stain; original magnification, ×400.) Rapid interpretation of the results of cytology samples quickly allows for differentiation between these neoplasms.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2019180097&amp;id=fig14b">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig15a" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2019180097/asset/images/large/rg.2019180097.fig15a.jpeg" height="2950" width="1302" aria-labelledby="fig15a" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 15a</span>. Recurrent SBL in a 58-year-old woman with a history of left breast cancer and mantle cell lymphoma who presented with a new right breast mass. <b>(a)</b> MLO mammogram shows a high-density retroareolar oval mass (arrow) with indistinct margins. <b>(b)</b> Gray-scale US image shows an irregular mixed-echogenicity mass with an echogenic rim (arrows). <b>(c, d)</b> Photomicrographs obtained with H-E stain (original magnification, ×20) <b>(c)</b> and Giemsa stain (original magnification, ×100) <b>(d)</b> show a dense infiltrate of atypical lymphoid cells that are small- to medium-sized with irregular nuclear contours, clumped chromatin, scant cytoplasm, and frequent mitoses (arrows in <b>d</b>).<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2019180097&amp;id=fig15a">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig15b" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2019180097/asset/images/large/rg.2019180097.fig15b.jpeg" height="891" width="1455" aria-labelledby="fig15b" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 15b</span>. Recurrent SBL in a 58-year-old woman with a history of left breast cancer and mantle cell lymphoma who presented with a new right breast mass. <b>(a)</b> MLO mammogram shows a high-density retroareolar oval mass (arrow) with indistinct margins. <b>(b)</b> Gray-scale US image shows an irregular mixed-echogenicity mass with an echogenic rim (arrows). <b>(c, d)</b> Photomicrographs obtained with H-E stain (original magnification, ×20) <b>(c)</b> and Giemsa stain (original magnification, ×100) <b>(d)</b> show a dense infiltrate of atypical lymphoid cells that are small- to medium-sized with irregular nuclear contours, clumped chromatin, scant cytoplasm, and frequent mitoses (arrows in <b>d</b>).<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2019180097&amp;id=fig15b">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig15c" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2019180097/asset/images/large/rg.2019180097.fig15c.jpeg" height="940" width="1455" aria-labelledby="fig15c" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 15c</span>. Recurrent SBL in a 58-year-old woman with a history of left breast cancer and mantle cell lymphoma who presented with a new right breast mass. <b>(a)</b> MLO mammogram shows a high-density retroareolar oval mass (arrow) with indistinct margins. <b>(b)</b> Gray-scale US image shows an irregular mixed-echogenicity mass with an echogenic rim (arrows). <b>(c, d)</b> Photomicrographs obtained with H-E stain (original magnification, ×20) <b>(c)</b> and Giemsa stain (original magnification, ×100) <b>(d)</b> show a dense infiltrate of atypical lymphoid cells that are small- to medium-sized with irregular nuclear contours, clumped chromatin, scant cytoplasm, and frequent mitoses (arrows in <b>d</b>).<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2019180097&amp;id=fig15c">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig15d" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2019180097/asset/images/large/rg.2019180097.fig15d.jpeg" height="806" width="1455" aria-labelledby="fig15d" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 15d</span>. Recurrent SBL in a 58-year-old woman with a history of left breast cancer and mantle cell lymphoma who presented with a new right breast mass. <b>(a)</b> MLO mammogram shows a high-density retroareolar oval mass (arrow) with indistinct margins. <b>(b)</b> Gray-scale US image shows an irregular mixed-echogenicity mass with an echogenic rim (arrows). <b>(c, d)</b> Photomicrographs obtained with H-E stain (original magnification, ×20) <b>(c)</b> and Giemsa stain (original magnification, ×100) <b>(d)</b> show a dense infiltrate of atypical lymphoid cells that are small- to medium-sized with irregular nuclear contours, clumped chromatin, scant cytoplasm, and frequent mitoses (arrows in <b>d</b>).<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2019180097&amp;id=fig15d">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div></section><section id="bibliography" role="doc-bibliography"><h2>References</h2><div role="list"><div role="listitem" data-has="label"><div class="label">1.</div><div id="r1" class="citations"><div class="citation"><div class="citation-content">Shim E, Song SE, Seo BK, Kim YS, Son GS. Lymphoma affecting the breast: a pictorial review of multimodal imaging findings. <em>J Breast Cancer</em> 2013;16(3):254–265.</div><div class="external-links"><div class="core-xlink-crossref"><a href="https://doi.org/10.4048/jbc.2013.16.3.254">Crossref</a></div><div class="core-xlink-pubmed"><a href="https://pubmed.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/24155754/">PubMed</a></div><div class="core-xlink-google-scholar"><a href="https://scholar.google.com/scholar_lookup?title=Lymphoma+affecting+the+breast%3A+a+pictorial+review+of+multimodal+imaging+findings&amp;author=E+Shim&amp;author=SE+Song&amp;author=BK+Seo&amp;author=YS+Kim&amp;author=GS+Son&amp;publication_year=2013&amp;journal=J+Breast+Cancer&amp;pages=254-265&amp;doi=10.4048%2Fjbc.2013.16.3.254&amp;pmid=24155754">Google Scholar</a></div></div></div></div></div><div role="listitem" data-has="label"><div class="label">2.</div><div id="r2" class="citations"><div class="citation"><div class="citation-content">Giardini R, Piccolo C, Rilke F. Primary non-Hodgkin’s lymphomas of the female breast. <em>Cancer</em> 1992;69(3): 725–735.</div><div class="external-links"><div class="core-xlink-crossref"><a href="https://doi.org/10.1002/1097-0142(19920201)69:3%3C725::AID-CNCR2820690320%3E3.0.CO;2-C">Crossref</a></div><div class="core-xlink-pubmed"><a href="https://pubmed.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/1730123/">PubMed</a></div><div class="core-xlink-google-scholar"><a href="https://s